She flipped to an empty page and noted the date. Below, she wrote “11.5.648–13.12.648”.
“Refreshing old memories?” Ivory asked and looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. “Do you think they’ll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left.”
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. “No,” as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari out, considering her a “flaw.” She was born deaf and was the only daughter in the family, her siblings were all boys.
Similar things happened to Ivory. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as though the world was changing. As punishment for this uniqueness, Ivory was given tasks that mostly involved being alone.
Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't matter much to Ivory, as Ivory gained a friend in the process.
“You have a birthday soon, right?” Ivory asked, thinking that the Princess had a birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad flicker in her light blue eyes.
“Do you want to celebrate your birthday?” Ivory asked, thinking back to the last time the Princess answered this question.
“No,” Kari knocked. Ivory knew this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was imprisoned in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory was just a baby at the time, but she remembered how upset the servants and the city dwellers were. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen. And that she somehow could predict things that would actually happen.
“So, what do you want to do?” Ivory asked. Kari looked excitedly at Ivory. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
White, various blue shades
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
“Are you going to get me these things?” Ivory asked the quiet princess, whose braids swung wildly from her vigorous knocking. “Yes?” Ivory giggled softly. The otherwise reserved princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
“Okay! Let's see each other later?” Ivory asked, stood up, and slithered through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her bedspread.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things outside her reach, like paints.
Ivory walked back down the corridors and tried to ignore the gossip of the maids.
“I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going back to this room.”
“I heard she eats children in this room.”
“She looks like a man, that's not normal?”
Ivory covered her ears because she couldn't just ignore the chatter and continued on. The artist's room was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Kari's door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons said to have created Frostfell. For a history-loving artist, the White Dragon on the door made sense.
Ivory opened the door, expecting the usual mess. Color splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered all over the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. However, an unexpected sight greeted her. The entire room was clean, and in front of a red velvet background stood a chair. On the chair sat Prince Aquilo, who was being portraitured at the time.
“Good morning, Ivory! Want to watch as your future king is being portraitured?” Aquilo asked, winking at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," Ivory said, largely ignoring him and gathering the things the quiet princess wanted. "I'm only here to get some art supplies."
"My little girl wants to leave already?" Aquilo asked. "I want you to stay!"
"I don't want to," Ivory found the art supplies on the list and put them in a box. "Besides, I'm not a girl."
The prince, however, had a different opinion. "Oh, sweetie, that's just a phase! As you get older, you'll grow out of it!" he said vaguely.
"I have to go," Ivory said, feeling uncomfortable with the prince's response. As Ivory walked away, all the nasty comments that he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came flooding back. I just want to get out of here.
“You're leaving already?” The prince suddenly appeared at the door and ignored the loud protests of the royal painter.
“That's no behavior for a future king!” Ivory said.
“No one will find out. People won't believe you and the painter will keep quiet if he values his life.” He looked at the painter briefly and then leaned in closer to Ivory. “Want to go on a date?” Ivory had been harassed in the past several times, but never by a prince, let alone the crown prince.
“Do you even know what the word ‘No’ means?” Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away.
“No,” Aquilo replied with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have anything he wants, doesn't know what the word “No” means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have at least 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He threw his hair back, which fluttered around in the cold air.
"Now get it! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced Ivory to look at him.
